STARTING DAY: 2026-03-17


PHASE 1 (6 Weeks)
Foundations — Biology + Math Refresh
The goal here is to get your biology and math to the point where models start making intuitive sense.

1) Neuroscience basics
Neurons, synapses, action potentials, brain regions. No math yet.
the single best free resource is Neuroscience Online (neuroscience.uth.tmc.edu) — a full open textbook from UT Houston. Pair it with the first two weeks of Coursera: Computational Neuroscience by the University of Washington (Rajesh Rao & Adrienne Fairhall). That course is free to audit and is specifically designed for people with a CS background.

2) Math refresh
Linear algebra, calculus, probability. Focus on intuition, not proofs.
3Blue1Brown's Essence of Linear Algebra and Calculus series on YouTube (free) is perfect — it's built for people who learned this before and need the intuition back, not a first-time learner. Estimated time: 10–12 hours total across both series.

3) Scientific Python
NumPy, Matplotlib, SciPy, Pandas. Data shapes and visualization.
NeuralDataScience.github.io (the Neural Data Science in Python book) is free and neuroscience-specific. Much better than a generic NumPy tutorial because every example is about real neural data shapes.

*
PHASE 2 (8 Weeks)
Core Computational Models
The essential text here is Theoretical Neuroscience by Dayan & Abbott. The PDF is freely available on Peter Dayan's website. It's the field's standard reference, and chapters 1–5 cover everything in this phase. Don't try to read it cover to cover — use it as a companion while you code.
For hands-on coding of models, Neuromatch Academy (neuromatch.io) is outstanding and completely free. Their computational neuroscience track has Jupyter notebooks for Hodgkin-Huxley, LIF neurons, and network models — with video lectures to go with each. This is probably the single most valuable resource in the whole curriculum.

1) Single neuron models
Hodgkin-Huxley, leaky integrate-and-fire. Simulate your first spike train.

2) Neural coding
Firing rates, tuning curves, population codes, spike sorting basics.

3) Network models
Synaptic plasticity, Hebbian learning, recurrent networks, Hopfield nets.
*
PHASE 3 (8 Weeks)
Data Analysis + Real Neural Data


1) Signal processing
Filtering, FFT, spectral analysis, spike detection. LFP and EEG fundamentals.
This is where it gets exciting. For signal processing, MNE-Python has excellent free tutorials covering everything from raw EEG to spectrograms. Their documentation is genuinely written as a learning resource.

2) Dimensionality reduction
PCA, t-SNE, UMAP on neural population data.
Neuromatch Academy again covers dimensionality reduction in their track, with great notebooks on PCA and UMAP applied to neural population data.

3) Open data platforms
DANDI, OpenNeuro, Allen Brain Atlas, IBL. Download and explore a dataset.
For open data, start with DANDI Archive (dandiarchive.org) — it uses NWB format (Neurodata Without Borders), which is becoming the standard. The Allen Brain Observatory is also exceptional if you're interested in visual cortex data — they have high-quality calcium imaging and electrophysiology datasets with a Python API.

*
PHASE 4 (6 Weeks)
Capstone — Your Own Analysis
Jonathan Pillow's GLM tutorial notebooks (freely available on GitHub) are the best introduction to generalized linear models for neural data. For the final write-up, treat a Jupyter notebook as your "paper" — narrative, code, plots, and interpretation all in one place.

1) GLMs + decoding
Fit generalized linear models. Decode behavior from neural activity.

2) Project + write-up
Choose a dataset, run a full pipeline, document findings in a notebook.
